Pokémon Go is a respectable hunt for health and happiness
It's fascinating to see how the world is changing.
Over the past decade, many have been worrying about teenagers and children no longer going out to play, but that they prefer to spend their free time watching screens.
Pokémon Go makes people get up from the couch and take part in some activity.
The screening time was originally limited to TV, then to video games and now to smartphones recently.
So it's great to see that technology and outdoor activity aren't mutually exclusive.
I refer to a craze called Pokémon Go. An application based on characters originally developed in the 1990s for video games (later, they became a cartoon series, playing cards, and other follow-up products).
Like many phenomena of pop culture, its popularity had somewhat diluted before the release of this new game in the United States, Australia and New Zealand early in July.
After that, the release of the game in other countries was postponed, as the huge popularity overloaded the servers.
In just days, Pokémon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as much as Twitter.
How does it work, then?
Explained in a nutshell, players use their smartphones to search for Pokémon that are tracked with GPS, and which can be “photographed” after discovery (using a phone screenshot) or “catch.”
A generation that played the game when they were younger has joined the craze and jumped up from the couch to the search.
In the United States, the game has led to a significant increase in the daily steps of the “average person”.
The Apple Watch app Cardiogram, which tracks 35,000 users, recently told the Washington Post that within two days of the game's release, the number of people moving 30 minutes a day jumped from 45 percent to 53 percent of users following the Cardiogram.
The company doesn't know who's playing Pokémon Go, it only sees the training level data.
Many public health campaigns’ calls for “find 30”, “get up on the couch” and “be active every day” have not yielded any result because most of the public health warnings are boring and cared for by people who seem unhappy.
However, the importance of exercise cannot be underestimated.
Regularly, people who exercise have a lower risk of cancer or depression.
Activity helps with weight management, high blood pressure and diabetes. Its benefits are too diverse for this list.
The beauty of Pokémon Go is that it makes people go out and do something they enjoy.
This is how the three pillars of health are covered: exercise, fresh air and sunshine, and fun.
Some people even make new friends when they hunt.
As usual, disapproving buzzkills are looking for things to complain about.
Yes, someone can walk into the door.
So what?
There's been a breakthrough.
Although there were previously apps like Fitbit that could be used to monitor activity, they didn't give a reason to move around the same way as this game.
The novelty will disappear and use will eventually subside.
However, due to the success of Pokémon, there will be other games that combine apps and virtual reality with real-world activity, helping many hunting people to be more active, in better shape, and healthier.
