The situation was compared immediately to 2007 and 2008, Vanhanen says.
This made investors nervous.
Institutional investors remained calmer, but private investors were nervous.
The snowball started spinning, and the fund after the fund had to close its doors.
The situation in Aberdeen was good due to the cash collected, but it, too, had to freeze its trading for six days.
According to Vanhanen, they did not actually close the commerce, but changed the pricing downwards.
In practice, investors were given time to consider whether it was now worthwhile to pull the money out in a panic.
Aberdeen's message was that if you don't have to take your money out now, it's not worth it, because it would be a loss.
It calmed the situation, and most of them withdrew the notification.
Since then, the market has been quite even, and now the market has been very peaceful for a couple of weeks, Vanhanen says.
He points out that, for example, there has been no similar turmoil in the Aberdeen Continental Europe Funds.
However, there were a lot of inquiries.
Unreasonable attention to real estate funds
According to Vanhanen, the closures of real estate funds received unreasonable attention.
