The Aberdeen lockdown lasted six days, and the company sold less than 10 properties out of 80 properties in London.
Some other funds are still closed.
Aviva Investors warned its investors this week that it might be sticking to its fund for 2017.
At the moment, there is uncertainty in the air, and economic growth forecasts have been ragged downwards, but the situation does not look "faderous" for Aberdeen.
The biggest issues now concern the future development of the British economy.
Despite the uncertainty, the situation has even brought new opportunities for some real estate investors, Vanhanen points out.
The price of the pound and the dollar is at its lowest in 30 years, and the market also has a 15% sale in relation to the time before the Brexit vote.
A dollar buyer can now buy the same property for up to 30 percent less.
There are many willing buyers, Vanhanen says.
Brexit has brought down the minus to the London real estate market
At two in the morning, the situation didn't look like much.
But at four o'clock, when Pertti Vanhanen, who is in charge of the real estate investments of the British real estate fund Aberdeen Asset Management, woke up again to look at the results of the Brexit vote, the situation was different.
The power word got in there.
I realized that this is now going to the side of plan B, Vanhanen says in his second home in Helsinki.
He immediately headed to work.
The City of London was already completely alive in the morning.
At the office, the normally silent TV screens were full of news, and the normally loud crowd was completely silenced to listen as Prime Minister David Cameron stepped in front of the camera this morning to tell about his resignation.
When the market opened, the display terminals flashed only red.
It was the kind of morning you never thought you would live, Vanhanen says.
Not because, despite the turmoil, Aberdeen, one of the UK's largest real estate funds, finished two real estate transactions on the day after the Brexit vote.
The atmosphere was confusing.
However, the company had prepared for the option well, which is why the situation was kind of calm, Vanhanen says.
Brexit vote begins correction
The vote was followed by a storm.
The pound collapsed, the British leadership went on an exchange.
The market began to anticipate drastic declines in the UK and London in particular.
Up to 20% of the office space in London was anticipated in the coming years.
Soon, a group of UK real estate funds began to freeze their trade one after the other.
Aberdeen did that for six days.
Now the storm has subsided, but uncertainty is still in the air.
However, it is not visible on the face of Vanhanen, who spent his last summer holidays this week in Helsinki.
He still thinks it's too early to say much about what Brexit will be.
So much is still open: how the difference will happen and how Scotland will react to the situation, for example.
The development of the London real estate market has already been first known.
CBRE's information on price development covers approximately one third of the market.
According to them, the prices of all properties in London fell by 3.3 per cent from June to July.
The City of London's office buildings accounted for 6.1 per cent of the negatives, Vanhanen lists.
The numbers aren't that bad, but they're monthly changes.
The monthly index was published in 1987, and only five months have been worse, says Vanhanen.
All the equally large drops hit the crisis years of 2007 and 2008.
It is also interesting because Brexit was quickly compared to Lehman's downfall and the global economic crisis that began in the US real estate market.
According to Vanhanen, the comparison is not quite accurate, as this is a home-made crisis in the UK.
The atmosphere is different.
The real estate market has not seen panic sales like that, but rather the willingness to sell to improve liquidity, Vanhanen says.
Funding is also available normally.
The repair could have been ahead anyway
In fact, the price correction movement is no wonder for him - such a thing could have been ahead even without Brexit.
According to Aberdeen's estimate, the prices of properties in London and other world's number one cities have been too high for years.
We have been saying for two years now that City and especially offices are overpriced, says Vanhanen.
The fall started very high.
London's prices have been upwards for four reasons, Vanhanen lists.
The British economy has grown strongly, the population of London as well.
Another big trend is that real estate is the last ownership category that is globalizing, Vanhanen says.
New players have entered the market from the Middle East and Asia, and more and more institutions and even private investors are looking for real estate investments abroad.
London is an easy destination as a well-known city.
In addition, prices have been fuelled by low interest rates, which has led, for example, pension companies to look for income from new destinations.
On top of this, the loan has been readily available - although, according to Vanhanen, the leverage has now been used clearly less than in the pre-crisis boom of 2008.
Decentralize, disperse
In London, the rise in prices stabilized last summer, Vanhanen says.
Aberdeen also began to lighten its holdings in London, and last year was a net seller.
There was some kind of turnaround to be expected, and now it's here.
What from now on?
It depends on how the British economy develops, Vanhanen says.
He does not dare to judge much for the future, but says that there is hardly any climbing spike.
The mood suggests that there is a downward or steady going ahead.
Vanhanen has already seen several stores up and down, as he has been in the real estate industry since 1988.
And he's still an optimist who believes that we can get through the bumps with work.
If you are well prepared for the risks, you are in a better position.
He believes in global decentralization.
If you have invested in one market, you are too much of a victim.
If you have diversified, the risks are also diversified, Vanhanen says.
