Another main reason for training a gun and explosives dog for Customs' duties is postal items passing through Helsinki Airport.
With the increased internet trade, up to 40 million mail items pass through the airport every year, including weapons supplies and explosives ordered from abroad.
In recent years, Customs has made an online store of about 300 discoveries related to purchases, luggage and air cargo of passenger aircraft, weapons, ammunition and explosives, and their precursors.
Heila will work in different parts of Helsinki Airport.
It will investigate checked baggage and mail.
In the future, it will be of great benefit to ports, as it can go through large container areas and mark areas that require more detailed research, says Grönberg.
Based on Heila's performance, Customs will assess whether more gun and explosives dogs will be trained in the future.
Grönberg is hopeful of the idea.
School in Kirkkonummi
The training of the Heila puppy is coordinated by the Customs Dog School in Kirkkonummi.
Suntio and Heila also go to the police and the Defence Forces' experts to train.
The police have strong experience in training dogs and the Finnish Defence Forces have expertise in explosives.
Customs, together with other authorities, decides what smells Heila is taught to identify.
Heila is always further trained as needed, says Grönberg.
Heila's colleagues at Helsinki Airport are Customs' six drug dogs and the money and drug dog Massi.
Labrador retriever Heila has been selected from a litter of ten puppies.
The selection criteria for the dog to be selected for the airport include briskness and hunting instinct, as well as calmness, because the dog is involved with weapons, explosives and the flow of people.
Heila, who lives at Suntio's home, is a close colleague to the customs inspector, but also a family member.
You can't get anywhere without Heila at home, Suntio laughs.
Subtle orders go to Heila from a single time.
Ilta-Sanomat's cameraman loses the camera's microphone cover to the fast dog, but Heila immediately returns the cover that looks like a soft toy from the "out" command.
A tough competition for working dogs
Heila's initial training will be completed next year.
There are still level tests ahead, next in October, where it will be assessed whether the training is sufficient for demanding tasks.
Heila can be seen in work tasks at Helsinki Airport next year, if everything goes according to plan.
Unfortunately, passengers cannot come and pet the dog wearing a work vest, reminds Suntio.
The cost of one working dog is about 60000-70000 euros per year for Customs.
Their working age is about seven to eight years, up to ten, after which they retire to their owner.
The working days can be long, from eight to ten hours, but the active work shares last only from ten minutes to a couple of hours.
