Scientists have previously argued that Venus's slow speed of rotation is explained by its thick atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus could have had a thin, earth-like atmosphere, and it could still have rotated slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
The planet probably had drier areas than Earth, but there was once enough water and geographical variation to enable life and protect against rapid water evaporation.
Early Venus also had the advantage of a 30 percent fainter sun.
“In a simulation of the GISS model, the slow rotation of Venus reveals it to the sun on the side of the day for almost two months at a time,” GISS researcher Anthony Del Genio said in a statement.
This warms the surface and produces rain that creates a thick layer of cloud that acts as an umbrella to protect the surface for much of the sun's heat.
As a result, the average climate temperatures are actually a few degrees cooler than Earth's current.
The model produced a story about the evolutionary phases of Venus, similar to what planetary scientists had previously assumed.
Although Venus probably had to be inhabited at some point, it was exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet light over several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapours burned in the ultraviolet light.
When its hydrogen escaped, all that remained was a thick carbon dioxide atmosphere with its deadly greenhouse gas phenomena - the Venus we know today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model of Venus in the Geophysical Research Letters.
Patrick Roy drops out of Avalanche coaching position
Patrick Roy resigned Thursday from the Colorado Avalanche coach and vice president of hockey, saying the reason was the lack of influence in the team's decision-making process.
Colorado Executive Vice President/President Joe Sakic confirmed the report and mentioned that the team will start looking for a new coach immediately.
“For the past three years, I have been doing my duty as the vice president and head coach of the Colorado Avalanche hockey affairs with enthusiasm, passion and determination,” Roy, 50, said in a statement.
I have thought long and hard during the summer about how I could improve this team to give it the depth it needs and take it to a higher level.
In order to achieve this, the view of the coach and the vice president of hockey matters must be fully aligned with the organization's vision.
He must also have the opportunity to influence the decisions that affect the performance of the team.
These conditions are not currently being met.
Sakic, who hired Roy on May 23, 2013, thanked Roy for his contribution to the team.
“Patrick told me about his decision today,” Sakic said.
We appreciate everything he has done for the organization, and we wish him luck in the future.
Roy was named the winner of the Jack Adams Award for the league's best coach in his first season with the Avalanche in 2013-14.
He led the team to 112 points and a mid-range victory, but Minnesota defeated Colorado in the first round of the playoffs, and the team hasn't made it to the next two years.
The Avalanche's games in the 2015-16 season ended in 39 wins, 39 losses and 4 draws, and the team lost by five points to the Wild, losing the Western Conference wild card playoff spot.
Roy, the goaltender selected for the Hall of Fame, won four Stanley Cups - two for both the Montreal Canadiens and the Avalanche.
North Sea oil workers continue negotiations and postpone strike
Labour disputes between North Sea oil workers over pay will be postponed when all parties to the dispute sit down for a new round of negotiations, leading negotiators said.
Strikes against the oil field service company Wood Group have been randomly arranged with North Sea drilling rigs run by Royal Dutch Shell.
“The Wood Group and the United and RMT unions can confirm that we have agreed to reopen the process of resolving the current dispute,” the statement said.
Over the next few weeks, we will hold several full-day meetings starting early next week so that we can take a fresh look at the problems.
According to the trade unions, their recent industrial action, which they say is the first in more than 25 years, was a protest against possible wage cuts of up to 30 percent.
This year, Wood Group cut the North Sea contractors' fees by approximately 9 per cent due to negative market pressure.
The company's remuneration deduction follows a 10% reduction of 10 per cent for contractors in its countries in 2014.
The company said further cuts would give the company the necessary room for manoeuvre to cope with the market downturn.
Shell, on the other hand, has cut thousands of people from their payroll and announced plans to leave oil and gas operations in as many as 10 countries, as a result of its operations lightening its operations as a result of its massive merger with the British energy company BG Group.
Energy companies are under pressure due to lower crude oil prices, and this economic situation is exacerbated by the UK's June decision to leave the European Union.
Scottish parliamentarian Dave Anderson met with union leaders earlier this week to discuss one of the generation's biggest North Sea labor disputes.
He said the North Sea is essential for the economy of the region.
“We need an economy that works for many, and not only for the few, both in the North Sea and across the country,” he said in a statement.
In 2016, the North Sea is expected to have fewer than 1.4 billion dollars in investments in new projects, while the average for the previous five years has been around US$7 billion.
Kepler measures the speed of star rotation in the Pleiades' star cluster
The latest mission of the Kepler Space Telescope has helped astronomers to compile the most complete list of the Star-streaking speeds of the Pleiades' Star Correction.
The new data helps astronomers understand why the stars of the cluster rotate at varying speeds, as well as how the orbital times are related to planet formation.
“We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will now learn more about the relationship between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system,” said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech’s Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the Pasadena Center
The Pleiade cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars of the group were born about 125 million years ago, and are just now reaching adulthood.
They're rolling at their top level now.
With their top speed, these adult stars will swell large amounts of star breeze.
When these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars, they brake the stars.
As the star gets older, its rotational speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star by tracking the appearance of recognizable star spots, such as sunspots.
The latest list of star rotational speeds suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, the bigger of which make pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
“In the ‘ballet’ of the Pleiads, we see that slow rotators tend to be more massive, while the fastest spins are usually very light stars,” Rebull said.
Because the Pleiade star cluster is so close, it is an ideal cosmic laboratory for evaluating the properties of stars at rotational speeds.
“The Pleiad star cluster offers an anchor star rotation to theoretical models that include both directions, younger and older,” Rebull said.
We still have a lot to learn about how, because and why stars slow down their speed of rotation and, so to speak, hang their ‘dance shoes’ on a nail.
Rebull and his colleagues described their latest analysis of the Pleiads' rotational speeds in three articles, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
